<section id="about-paintings-object">

  <div class="row">
    <div class="small-12 columns">
      
      <h2 class="animate fadeIn featured-object-tagline">This window saw the truth.</h2>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="row featured-objects">
    <div class="small-12 columns">

      <ul class="clearing-thumbs small-block-grid-3" data-clearing>

        <li class="medium-4 columns animate fadeIn featured-object-1">
          <div>
            <a href="VanGogh--Bedroom--1888--VanGoghMuseumAmsterdam--1400.jpg" title="View larger version of this painting">
              <img data-caption="Vincent van Gogh. <em>The Bedroom</em>, 1888. Van Gogh Museum, Amsterdam (Vincent van Gogh Foundation)." alt="Vincent van Gogh. <em>The Bedroom</em> (Window detail), 1888. Van Gogh Museum, Amsterdam (Vincent van Gogh Foundation)." src="detail-window-VanGoghMuseumAmsterdam.jpg">
            </a>
            <h3>Amsterdam</h3>
          </div>
        </li>

        <li class="medium-4 columns animate fadeIn featured-object-2">
          <div>
            <a href="VanGogh--Bedroom--1889--ArtInstituteChicago--1400.jpg" title="View larger version of this painting">
              <img data-caption="Vincent van Gogh. <em>The Bedroom</em>, 1889. The Art Institute of Chicago, Helen Birch Bartlett Memorial Collection." alt="Vincent van Gogh. <em>The Bedroom</em> (Window detail), 1889. The Art Institute of Chicago, Helen Birch Bartlett Memorial Collection." src="detail-window-ArtInstituteChicago.jpg">
            </a>
            <h3>Chicago</h3>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="medium-4 columns animate fadeIn featured-object-3">
          <div>
            <a href="VanGogh--Bedroom--1889--MuseedOrsayParis--1400.jpg" title="View larger version of this painting">
              <img data-caption="Vincent van Gogh. <em>The Bedroom</em>, 1889. Mus&eacute;e d'Orsay, Paris, sold to national museums under the Treaty of Peace with Japan, 1959." alt="Vincent van Gogh. <em>The Bedroom</em> (Window detail), 1889. Mus&eacute;e d'Orsay, Paris, sold to national museums under the Treaty of Peace with Japan, 1959." src="detail-window-MuseedOrsayParis.jpg">
            </a>
            <h3>Paris</h3>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ul>
      
    </div>

  </div>

  <div class="row featured">
    <div class="medium-9 columns">
      <p>An open-and-shut case? Not exactly.</p>

<p>In the first <em>Bedroom</em> the window seems to be almost completely shut due to the angle of the window frames. In the second, both windows appear to be slightly open. In the third version, only the right window seems slightly open. The height and width of the windows also vary across the paintings.</p>

<p>Thanks to advanced technology called scanning macro-X-ray fluorescence spectroscopy (a type of X-ray that scans the surface to identify the unique elemental makeup of pigments), we also now know that Van Gogh used different pigments for the various windows. For the first <em>Bedroom</em>, Van Gogh painted the window frame with emerald green but for the second used a mixture of emerald and viridian greens.</p>

    </div>
    <div class="medium-3 columns">
      <div class="panel">
        <h3>Want to find out more?</h3>
        <p>Visit the exhibition:</p>
        

  
